<dl id="n11144g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11144g">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11144g"> 144(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> &amp; &mdash; out / rotten / riding her stallion / brisants</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Le roi Gradlon se jeta sur son cheval, et sa fille en croupe derri&egrave;re lui. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Envelopp&eacute; par la mar&eacute;e montante, Morvark <font color="green">[the horse]</font> avait grimp&eacute; sur un &eacute;cueil. Le poil h&eacute;riss&eacute;, le cheval regardait devant lui une chose terrible. A la lueur de la lune rouge, Gradlon vit le gouffre de Plogoff. La bouche d&apos;enfer revomissait le vagues monstres englouties avec <mark>les brisants</mark>. A chaque hoquet, elle rendait une forme humaine. Cadavre ou fant&ocirc;me? Gradlon reconnut les amants de sa fille. <br><font color="green">[King Gradlon threw himself on his horse, and his daughter behind him. [...]</font> Wrapped by the rising tide, Morvark <font color="green">[the horse]</font> had climbed a rock. The hair bristling, the horse looked in front of him a terrible thing. In the light of the red moon, Gradlon saw the abyss of Plogoff. The mouth of hell revived the waves monsters engulfed with the breakers. With each hiccup she made a human form. Corpse or ghost? Gradlon recognized the lovers of his daughter.] <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLG" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLG"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1921, 1892) 225-6</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The bottom of the page has been torn off</mm> </dd></dl>
